/**/
Master list:
    Cross-reference: granular stubs remain above (`NEXT`, `TODO`, `billing + beta`)—merge duplicates against this list as you complete work.

    + (P1) Collaboration, workflow, and communication
        + 1. Unified in-app inbox / notification center (invites, approvals, assignments, completions, rejections)—backed by real queries, not demo UI.
        - ! 2. Email notifications for high-signal events (invite, approval needed, assignment, rejection, subscription expiring)—with per-user preferences.
        + 3. In-app comments or threads on tasks (optionally projects)—with @mentions if you add them.
        + 4. @mentions in comments tied to notification delivery.
        - ! 5. Task-level activity stream (status, budget, materials)—distinct from global audit.
        - 6. File attachments other than photos (PDFs, specs, drawings) if users expect document trails.
        - 7. Version note or “reason for change” on sensitive edits (budget, dates, approvals).
        - 8. Templates for short messages (“Material delayed”, “Awaiting client sign-off”) for mobile speed.
        - 9. Shareable deep links to a task/project (logged-in or read-only token for vendors/clients later).
        + 10. Completion approvals: before approving task completion, auto-check for outstanding requests (material, payment, assignment, etc.) and block or warn.

    (P2) Discovery, navigation, and information architecture
        1. Global search (orgs, projects, tasks, people)—wire existing cmdk primitive app-wide.
        2. Recent items and favorites / pinned projects.
        3. Breadcrumbs on deep pages (project → phase → task).
        4. Deep linking for every meaningful screen (share URL, refresh-safe).
        5. Keyboard shortcuts (e.g. open search, go dashboard) for power users on desktop.
        6. Filters saved as views (“My overdue”, “This site only”).
        7. Cross-links from dashboard cards into filtered lists.
        8. Consistent page titles (`metadata` per route) for bookmarks and tabs.
        9. 404 / error pages with next steps and preserved auth context.
        10. Organisations list: filters + search (admin backlog).
        11. Projects list: filters + search (admin backlog).
        12. Admin home/dashboard: Recent activity component fed by real events (not static demo).

    (P3) Reporting, analytics, and Statistics
        1. Owner/admin statistics dashboard: throughput, spend vs planned, completion rates, overdue counts.
        2. Time-range filters and comparison vs previous period.
        3. Breakdown by organisation / project / phase.
        4. Export chart/table data as CSV behind tier gates if tiers promise analytics depth.
        5. Scheduled exports (email CSV weekly)—premium lever.
        6. Material usage vs planned rollups.
        7. Approval SLA metrics (time pending).
        8. Align plan marketing copy with implemented tier differences (no “advanced stats” without delivery).
        9. Surfaces for project progress and linked tasks on project list/detail (admin backlog).
        10. Budget per sq ft (organisation and/or project) if required by workflows.

    (P4) Vendors, procurement, and field alignment
        1. Vendors directory (contact, categories, default terms).
        2. Link materials / requests to vendors where relevant.
        3. Purchase or request history per vendor.
        4. Preferred vendor flags on material types.
        5. Light price history or last-paid hints when logging spend.
        6. Material costing calculator in-product.
        7. Settings: setup/configure material average cost (admin backlog).

    (P5) Permissions, roles, and governance
        1. Explicit role matrix (owner, admin, manager, contributor, viewer, finance-only, etc.).
        2. Project-level roles distinct from org-level where needed.
        3. Field-safe mode: hide sensitive totals for roles that must not see money.
        4. Invite revocation and expiring invite links.
        5. Transfer organisation ownership with safeguards.
        6. Org-level audit export for admins (compliance).
        7. IP allowlist or SSO—enterprise backlog.
        8. Organisation member roles: when changing roles, enforce at least one admin remains.
        9. Project member roles: when changing roles, enforce at least one supervisor remains.
        10. Financial visibility: do not show budget/spend to supervisors or non-admins—admin-only (UI + RLS aligned).
        11. Employees: allow voluntarily leaving an organisation (self-remove / leave flow).

    (P6) Billing, subscription, and commercial UX
        1. In-app subscription status card (plan, renewal/end, limits used vs max).
        2. Upgrade/downgrade UX copy and enforced transitions—even if fulfillment stays manual for now.
        3. Invoice / receipt artefact or external link placeholder until gateway lands.
        4. Grace period policy surfaced in UI when `current_period_end` approaches.
        5. Seat usage indicator with clear definition of “seat”.
        6. Fair messaging when limits hit—who must hold the subscription (owner vs member).
        7. Organisation-level budget: set and edit org budget; allocate from org pool to projects (TODO backlog).

    (P7) Auth, account, and profile
        1. Email verification UX polish (resend, clear errors).
        2. Session/security area: password change; sign-out everywhere when supported.
        3. MFA when policy supports it—especially for paying owners.
        4. Account deletion UX: confirm modal, consequences, URL suitable for store policies.
        5. Data export request (“Download my data”) aside from delete.
        6. Profile completeness prompts (photo, phone for coordination).

    (P8) Mobile, responsive, and Capacitor readiness
        1. Touch targets and spacing audit on every primary flow.
        2. Safe areas and scroll containment vs bottom nav / keyboard overlap.
        3. Pull-to-refresh or explicit refresh where realtime might lag.
        4. Offline messaging: banner when network drops; eventual queued actions if you add offline writes.
        5. Biometric app lock (Capacitor)—later.
        6. Native push (Capacitor): mobile notifications for workflow signals (invites, approvals, assignments, completions, rejections)—real delivery wired to the same events as the in-app inbox, not placeholders; mind Play/App policies. (Moved from former P1.11.)
        7. Store data safety text aligned with actual SDKs and data flows.
        8. Mobile responsiveness pass across flows (NEXT general backlog—not only Capacitor shell).

    (P9) Performance and perceived speed
        1. Route-level `loading.tsx` and skeletons matching final layout (avoid layout jump).
        2. List virtualization if tables grow large.
        3. Image optimization pipeline for uploads (caps, optional client compression).
        4. Pagination or infinite scroll on heavy lists.
        5. Debounced search and filters.
        6. Realtime subscription hygiene: unsubscribe on unmount; avoid duplicate channels on navigation.
        7. Audit authenticated API chatter for redundant fetches.
        8. Database optimisation (indexes, hot queries) alongside recurring RLS reviews (NEXT general backlog).

    (P10) Accessibility (WCAG-minded)
        1. Focus order and visible focus rings on custom components.
        2. Screen reader labels on icon-only buttons (sidebar, mobile nav).
        3. Form errors tied to fields (`aria-describedby`).
        4. Colour contrast pass on text and charts.
        5. Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` where Framer Motion runs.
        6. Skip link to main content on authenticated shell.

    (P11) Internationalisation and locale
        1. Locale-ready dates and numbers (centralise ₹ and formatting).
        2. Timezone clarity on deadlines (local vs org timezone).
        3. i18n string architecture—even if English-only at launch.

    (P12) Security and abuse resistance
        1. Rate limiting on sensitive APIs (`unlock-with-code`, auth-adjacent routes).
        2. CAPTCHA or backoff on signup/login if abuse appears.
        3. Content Security Policy and standard security headers on Vercel.
        4. Keep webhook signature verification consistent across payment paths.
        5. Periodic audit: service role never in client bundles.
        6. RLS regression checklist after schema/policy changes; no prod dev “disable RLS” scripts.
        7. Full security code review with tracked remediation (TODO backlog).

    (P13) Compliance, privacy, and trust surfaces
        1. Privacy/terms/cookies reviewed against actual analytics, email, Capacitor SDKs.
        2. Cookie consent if non-essential cookies or marketing pixels ship.
        3. Subprocessors list (Supabase, Vercel, email, error tracker).
        4. Data retention statement (tasks, photos, logs)—optional automated purge later.
        5. Incident channel (status page or `/status` later).
        6. Privacy policy, terms of service, cookies/data pages: keep deployed copy aligned with actual product, billing mode, and SDKs (TODO backlog).

    (P14) Observability and supportability
        1. Error tracking (e.g. Sentry) with scrubbed user/org context.
        2. Structured logs on API routes with correlation ids.
        3. Support runbook or light admin tools for common fixes (stuck invite, wrong tier).
        4. Feature flags for risky launches (statistics v1, vendors v1).

    (P15) QA depth
        1. `next build` in CI so broken deploys fail PRs.
        2. E2E: signup → org → project → task → approval critical path.
        3. Contract tests on entitlement parsing and limit enforcement.
        4. Cross-browser matrix (Chrome, Safari, Firefox; mobile Safari).
        5. Optional axe accessibility scan in CI.
        6. Smoke checklist before ship: migration `09` limits applied in prod DB; org/project/seat caps; error surfaces + toasts; subscriber vs member journeys (Phase E5).
        7. Production Supabase: Auth URL configuration, redirect URLs, email templates verified end-to-end (Phase F1).
        8. Keep baseline UX: new flows ship with button loading states + toast/error feedback (legacy NEXT items marked DONE).

    (P16) Marketing, SEO, and store-facing polish
        1. Landing: screenshots and sections matching real UI; pricing honesty vs code unlock.
        2. `robots.txt` and `sitemap.xml` if public discovery matters.
        3. `manifest.json`, icons, theme colour for install/PWA feel before Capacitor.
        4. Open Graph / Twitter assets per major public route.
        5. Canonical URLs and `NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL` correctness for redirects.
        6. Front page / marketing landing iteration (TODO backlog—copy, structure, proof points).
        7. Sitewide visual makeover pass (TODO backlog—typography, spacing, hero, screenshots).

    (P17) Microcopy, empty states, and onboarding
        1. First-run checklist on dashboard (dismissible, progress).
        2. Empty states with one primary CTA per list view.
        3. Tooltip glossary for domain terms (phase, approval, spend vs planned).
        4. Inline validation on long forms (create project, materials).
        5. Success copy that states what happens next—not only toasts.
        6. Guided tutorial or first-run tour for new accounts (Phase E4).

    (P18) Visual and brand consistency
        1. Dark mode audit (charts, borders, banners).
        2. Spacing scale pass—cards, tables, modals.
        3. Distinct loading vs empty vs error visuals everywhere.
        4. Light illustration/iconography on key empty states.
        5. Colour scheme refinement pass (NEXT general backlog).

    (P19) Integrations and extensibility (longer horizon)
        1. Calendar export (iCal) for task deadlines.
        2. Outbound webhooks (“task completed”) for customer systems.
        3. Zapier/Make or CSV SFTP—enterprise storyline.
        4. Accounting-friendly export formats (generic ledger CSV).
        5. Payment gateway: checkout + subscription webhooks when moving beyond manual unlock (`Later:` backlog).
        6. Capacitor Android / Play Store packaging when going native (`Later:` backlog).
        7. Job costing / Tally (or equivalent accounting) integration (`Later:` backlog).
        8. Payouts workflow if you pay subcontractors/suppliers through the product (`Later:` backlog).

    (P20) Codebase cleanup tied to polish
        + 1. Remove or replace demo notification UI — done: `InboxBell` + deleted `DashboardNotifications`.
        2. Wire command palette globally once search exists.
        3. Fix nav duplication / consistency (`navitems.ts` duplicate Settings entries).
        4. Align Statistics nav visibility with owner shell and future tier rules.
        5. Project details: fix used budget not showing (admin backlog).
        6. Create Project: save custom templates in DB and list them in the template picker (admin backlog).
        7. Project details: ship complete Settings tab (admin backlog).
        8. Admin Settings: finish remaining screens (overlap with material averages—see P4).
        9. Vendors admin area: implement end-to-end (screens + API + RLS)—full scope under P4.

    (P21) Billing beta — close-out checklist (internal phases B–F)
        1. Phase B–D: verify in prod—subscriber gates, org/project/seat caps, renewal banner + employee empty states, billing in nav, post-unlock entitlement refresh.
        2. Phase E: billing card detail (plan, status, provider, periods, caps); user menu shows correct name/email.
        3. Phase E: `/statistics` routes + owner vs member behaviour matches shipping intent.
        4. Phase F: legal copy fits manual/beta billing; beta comms + final launch pass.
        5. Track payment-gateway cutover separately under P19.5 when leaving beta.

